# KMS in practice — S3, EBS, RDS

## S3 — four modes

| Mode | Keys | Note |
|---|---|---|
| **SSE-S3** | AWS-managed | default, cheapest, no audit |
| **SSE-KMS** | KMS / CMK | every GET → KMS `Decrypt`, logged |
| **SSE-C** | you supply | AWS never stores the key |
| **Client-side** | app encrypts | AWS never sees plaintext |

**Gotcha:** SSE-KMS calls KMS on **every GET** → hits the rate limit at scale. Fix: **S3 Bucket Keys** (one bucket-level data key across many objects).

## EBS & RDS

- Encryption chosen **at creation** — covers data, snapshots, replicas
- **Can't** encrypt an existing unencrypted volume/instance in place → **snapshot → copy encrypted → restore**
- **EBS:** turn on **account-level default encryption**
- **RDS:** KMS at rest, **TLS** in transit

**Through-line:** KMS is picked **at create time**, transparent at rest, hard to add later.
